'''Sebuku''' (also spelled '''Seboekoe''' or '''Sebeekee''') is an island in the [[Sunda Strait]] between [[Java]] and [[Sumatra]]. It is one of the larger islands in the strait and lies just {{convert|2.5|km|mi}} to the north of [[Sebesi]] and {{convert|2.3|km|mi}} south of [[Sumatra]].<ref name="Yukawa2">{{harvnb|Junichi Yukawa|p=2}}</ref> It is administratively part of [[South Lampung Regency]], [[Lampung]].<ref name="kablamsel">{{cite web |url=http://www.lampungselatankab.go.id/?q=node/8 |title=Profile dan Potensi Kabupaten Lampung Selatan |author= |date= |work= |language=Indonesia|trans_title=Profile and Potential of South Lampung Regency|publisher=Government of South Lampung Regency|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref>

==History==
At the time of the 1883 eruption of [[Krakatoa]], Sebuku was uninhabited, but a village on Sebuku Ketjil, a small island to its east, was completely wiped out. Official records give 150 killed, with 70 being non-residents.<ref>{{harvnb|Simke|Fiske}}</ref>

In the 1920s, [[copra]] palms were planted on Sebuku to satisfy the growing market. However, due to a lack of maintenance the palms eventually withered and died.<ref>{{harvnb|Touwen|p=176}}</ref>

In 1999 a sunken [[Japan]]ese ship was found near Sebuku by divers preparing for an underwater photography contest. Its age is unknown.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunken Japanese ship spotted |url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/1999/08/19/sunken-japanese-ship-spotted.html|date=19 August, 1999 |work=|publisher=''[[The Jakarta Post]]'' |accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref>

==Geography==
Sebuku is a low island, located in the eastern part of the mouth of [[Lampung Bay]],<ref name="Darsono110">{{harvnb|Darsono and Aziz|p=110}}</ref> {{convert|2.5|km|mi}} north of [[Sebesi]] and {{convert|2.3|km|mi}} south of [[Sumatra]].<ref name="Yukawa2"/> It covers a total area of {{convert|17.71|km2|mi2}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bphn.go.id/data/documents/07pdlampung006.doc|title=Peraturan Daerah Provinsi Lampung Nomor 6 Tahun 2007 tentang Rencana Pembangun Jangka Panjang Daerah Provinsi Lampung Tahun 2005 - 2025|publisher=Government of Lampung|language=Indonesian|trans_title=Local Legislation of the Province of Lampung Number 6 of the Year 2007 regarding the Long-Term Development Plans for Lampung from 2005 - 2025|accessdate=6 July 2011}}</ref> It is administratively part of [[South Lampung Regency]], [[Lampung]].<ref name="kablamsel"/>

Sebuku has a centre composed of [[andesite]], indicating an early volcanic history. This centre has been dated to the [[Quaternary]] and has been called an early manifestation of [[volcanism]] in the Sunda Strait.<ref>{{harvnb|Barber ''et al.''|p=109}}</ref> The substrate on the northern side of the island consists of [[fossilization|fossilized]] coral, mud and sand, while on the eastern side of the island the substrate consists of mud, sand, gravel, and both live and fossilized coral.<ref name="Darsono110"/> The outside is fringed by a [[reef]].<ref name="Darsono105">{{harvnb|Darsono and Aziz|p=105}}</ref>

{{wide image|Sebuku Island.jpg|1800px|A panoramic montage of Sebuku Island}}

==Ecology==
Sebuku, along with Sebesi, has been noted as a "stepping stone" for butterfly migration between Sumatra and Krakatoa. There are numerous butterfly species from both [[Java]] and Sumatra on Sebuku.<ref>{{harvnb|Junichi Yukawa|p=8}}</ref> Four species of ants have been found on Sebuku, fewer than Sebesi and Krakatoa.<ref name="Asyifa2">{{harvnb|Asfiya ''et al.''|p=2}}</ref> These included ants not found on Krakatoa, thought to be descended from fauna that survived the [[1883 eruption of Krakatoa|1883 eruption]].<ref>{{harvnb|Asfiya ''et al.''|p=8}}</ref>

The waters near Sebuku have fewer [[echinoderm]]s than further into the Lampung Bay. This is thought to be from exploitation and poor [[resource management]].<ref>{{harvnb|Darsono and Aziz|p=111}}</ref>

Due to cultivation, few natural forests remain on Sebuku.<ref name="Asyifa2"/> However, along the eastern coast of Sebuku there are many [[mangrove]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Soeroyo and Suyarso|p=97}}</ref> There are also tropical plants found throughout the island.<ref name="Darsono105"/>

==Tourism==
Sebuku is a popular destination for [[snorkeling]] and [[diving]], with tourists generally arriving by boat from Canti village on Sumatra.<ref>{{harvnb|Vaisutis|p=482}}</ref>

